What is the difference between JDK and JVM?
A.JDK is a software development kit to develop applications in Java and JVM executes java byte codes and provides environment to execute it.

What is the difference between JVM and JRE?
A. JVM executes byte codes and provides environment to execute it and JRE is part of the Java Development kit(JDK) and is a set of component to create and run a Java application.

What is compile time and run time?
A.Compile time when the programming code is converted to a machine code(binary code) and the run time is when the programme is running and it generally occurs after the compile time.

What is heap?
A. Heap is i a dynamique memory that is used to create instance or variable.

How java manage it's memory?
A. Java is managing it's memory by using stack memory,heap memory and garbage collection.

What is the difference between String, StringBuffer and StringBuilder?
A. String is immutable class while StringBuffer and StringBuilder are mutable classes.
   StringBuffer is thread-safe and synchronised while StringBuilder is not.
   StringBuffer is faster than StringBuilder.

What is Singleton class?
A. A singleton class is a class that can have only one object at a time and it is used to protect class and objects.

What is Serialization and Deserialization?
A.Serialization is a mechanism of converting the state of an object into a byte stream.
  Deserialization is the reverse process where the byte stream is used to recreate the actual Java object in memory.

when to use transient variable in java?
A.Transient is a variable modifier that is used in serialization when we do not want to save a value of a particular variable in a file.

Difference between while and do..while loop?
A.While loop check the condition first then executes the statement, do...while loop executes the statement then check the condition.

What is Enum?
A. An enum type is a special data type that enables for a variable to be a set of predefined constants. The variable must be equal to one of the values that have been predefined for it.
  Common examples include compass directions (values of NORTH, SOUTH, EAST, and WEST) and the days of the week.

What is Iterator?
A.An iterator is an object that has methods that allow you to proccess a collection of items one at a time.

Which one will take more memory, an int or Integer?
A. integer will take more memory.

Why is String Immutable in Java?
A.String in Java is immutable which means once you create a String object the content of that string cannot be modified.
  The key benefits of keeping this class as immutable are caching, security, synchronization, and performance.

What is constructor chaining in Java?
A. Constructor chaining is the process of calling one constructor from another constructor with respect to current object.

The difference between Serial and Parallel Garbage Collector?
A. Serial is a singlethread: the deletion of the objects are done one after the other. parallel is multi-thread: the deletion of the objects are done at the same time.

What is JIT stands for?
A.Just In Time

Explain Java Heap space and Garbage collection?
A. Heap space is the available memory for storing object, Garbage collection is the deletion of all unused objects to clear space for new objects.

Can you guarantee the garbage collection process?
A.No, garbage collection does not guarantee that the programme will not run out of memory because it only clears space from deleting unused objects.
  Thus, we can have a programme free of unused objects and no memory space can be cleared.

What is the difference between stack and heap in Java?
A.Stack is only used for the method while heap is used throughout the application.

What is reflection in java and why is it useful?
A.reflection is a feature in Java programming that allows an executing java programme to examine or introspect upon itself, and manipulate internal properties of the program.

what is multithreading in java?
A.Multithreading refers to a process of executing two or more threads simultaneously for maximum utilization of the CPU.

What is the use of synchronization in Java?
A.Synchronization is capability to control the access of multiple  threads to any shared ressources, it is used for reliable communication between threads.

What is Framework?
A.Framework is the  body of prewritten code used by developers to create apps using the Java programming language.

What are the testing Framework available in java?
A. some of the testing frameworks are: Selenium, Junit, TestNG, Cucumber

Difference between jUnit and testNG?
A.JUnit is an open-source framework used to trigger and write tests, TestNG is a Java-based framework that is an upgraded option for running tests.
JUnit does not support to run parallel tests, TestNG can run parallel tests.

What are the dependencies for this project?
A.MySql dependencies, mangoDb dependencies and Junit dependencies

what is dependency injection in java?
A.Dependency injection is the concept in which objects get other required objects from outside.
  Dependency injection can be implemented in any programming language. The general concept behind dependency injection is called Inversion of Control.

What is static binding and dynamic binding?
A. The static binding uses Type information for binding while Dynamic binding uses Objects to resolve to bind.
   Static binding is used to resolve Overloading methods and dynamique binding is used in overridden methods.










